<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="growth-referral-programs">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>growth-marketer</domain>
    <summary>Turn satisfied customers into acquisition channels via TRIGGER-ACTION-REWARD. Double-sided rewards at 20-50% CAC, trigger at win moments, idempotent fulfillment to prevent double-crediting.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>referral</tag>
      <tag>growth</tag>
      <tag>acquisition</tag>
      <tag>word-of-mouth</tag>
      <tag>viral</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Growth Referral Programs</title>

    <summary>Structured programs that turn satisfied customers into acquisition channels via the TRIGGER-ACTION-REWARD model. Referred users have 4x LTV vs paid-acquisition users and cost 50-80% less to acquire. Referral programs fail when incentives are too weak, the sharing flow is hidden, or fraud is not prevented. Key design decisions: double-sided vs single-sided reward, reward sizing at 20-50% of CAC, trigger placement at win moments (not first visit), and idempotent reward fulfillment to prevent double-crediting.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Word-of-mouth is the highest-converting acquisition channel but is left to chance without a program. Referred users have 4x LTV vs paid-acquisition users (they arrived with social proof) and cost 50-80% less to acquire. Referral programs fail when incentives are too weak, the sharing flow is hidden, or fraud is not prevented.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Product has PMF and at least a few hundred happy customers (NPS positive, D30 retention &gt; 30%).</item>
        <item>CAC via paid channels is rising and unit economics allow a 20-50% CAC reward to referrers.</item>
        <item>LTV is high enough (&gt; 3x CAC) that double-sided incentives are sustainable.</item>
        <item>An agent loop can own design → tracking → email/in-app promotion → fraud review → KPI reporting.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-PMF or NPS still negative — referrals propagate churn, not growth.</item>
        <item>Low-margin commodities where a $10 give/$10 get reward is not sustainable.</item>
        <item>B2B with long enterprise sales cycles where sales-assisted introductions outperform self-serve referrals.</item>
        <item>Compliance-heavy verticals (regulated finance, health) where incentivized referrals trigger jurisdiction-specific disclosure rules.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="reward-types">
      <p>How to design the reward structure in a referral program.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Default to double-sided rewards (both referrer and referee benefit); single-sided programs feel exploitative and convert 20-30% worse on the invitee side.</statement>
        <rationale>The invitee receiving a reward removes the psychological burden of accepting a favor and signals the program is legitimate, not just a multi-level scheme.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Double-sided cash/credit: best for SaaS and e-commerce with high LTV</item>
        <item>Referrer-only: acceptable for very low-margin products</item>
        <item>Tiered: more referrals unlock larger rewards — drives power-user participation</item>
        <item>Product-based: free storage, free month — retains cost within product margin</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Size the reward at 20-50% of CAC; recompute as CAC drifts rather than fixing a round-number amount permanently.</statement>
        <rationale>A reward below 20% of CAC is often not motivating. Above 50%, the economics deteriorate relative to paid channels. LTV must exceed 3x CAC for a double-sided program to be sustainable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="trigger-points">
      <p>When to ask users for referrals in their journey.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Ask for referrals at win moments: post-purchase, after a positive review, after a support win, at feature milestones, at subscription renewal.</statement>
        <rationale>Satisfaction is at its peak at win moments. Users are primed to share when they have just experienced value — not on first visit, not during checkout.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Do NOT ask: first visit (no relationship established)</item>
        <item>Do NOT ask: after a complaint or support escalation</item>
        <item>Do NOT ask: during the checkout flow (distracts from conversion)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="reducing-sharing-friction">
      <p>Minimize friction in the sharing flow to maximize invites per referrer (the "i" in K-factor).</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Provide a one-click copy link as the primary sharing mechanism; add email, social, and in-app invite as secondary options. Long referral links must be shortened.</statement>
        <rationale>Every extra click in the sharing flow reduces i by 10-20%. Copy-link is the highest-participation channel because it requires no authentication or form.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Unique link: one click to copy, short URL</item>
        <item>Email invite: pre-written message, recipient can be pasted</item>
        <item>Social share: Twitter, LinkedIn, WhatsApp buttons</item>
        <item>QR code: for physical/in-person contexts</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="fraud-prevention">
      <p>Fraud prevention, deterministic rules, and human-in-loop workflows for operating a referral program.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use deterministic fraud rules (IP overlap, payment-method match, signup velocity) rather than LLM judgment; flag candidates for human review rather than auto-banning.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs are not reliable fraud adjudicators. Deterministic feature computation is auditable and consistent; final ban decisions require a human-in-loop to avoid legal exposure.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Require email verification before reward eligibility</item>
        <item>Waiting period: reward releases only after referee's first real action (purchase, N-day retention)</item>
        <item>Flag users with &gt;5 invites in 24h or shared payment method as fraud candidates</item>
        <item>Minimum purchase requirement prevents disposable account abuse</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="key-metrics">
      <p>Essential metrics to track and their targets.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Participation rate = referrers / total customers; target 10-15%</item>
        <item>Referral rate = referrals per referrer; target 2-5</item>
        <item>Conversion rate = signups / invite clicks; target 10-25%</item>
        <item>K-factor = invites/user × conversion; target varies by product type</item>
        <item>CAC via referral = program cost / referred customers; target &lt;50% of paid CAC</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="promotion-sequence">
      <p>Email and in-app promotion timing and messaging.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Email 1: Program announcement with unique link</item>
        <item>Email 2: Success story (customer who earned rewards)</item>
        <item>Email 3: Reminder with current reward status</item>
        <item>Email 4: Limited-time bonus (double rewards) — use sparingly</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>How to use AI agents to design, operate, and optimize a referral program.</p>
      <p>A growth agent designs the program (incentive curve, trigger map, fraud rules) on Opus, then a Sonnet agent generates landing-page copy, email sequences and dashboard SQL. A Haiku operator polls the referral platform API daily, calculates K-factor and participation rate, and surfaces anomalies. Fraud-review and any reward &gt;$X is escalated to human via a queue file.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-growth-agent (Opus) — program design, reward sizing vs CAC, loop economics; Generic copy/Sonnet subagent — emails, landing page, in-app modal copy; Generic data/Haiku subagent — daily K-factor pull from ReferralCandy/GrowSurf/Mixpanel.</p>
      <p>Prompt pattern: "Design a double-sided referral program for {product} with CAC=${cac}, LTV=${ltv}, monthly churn={churn}%. Output: reward structure, 5 trigger points, fraud rules, K-factor target, and a 4-email launch sequence. Constrain reward to &lt;={max_pct}% of CAC." and "Analyze last 30d referral events from {source}. Compute participation rate, invites/referrer, conversion rate, K. Flag users with &gt;5 invites in &lt;24h or shared payment method as fraud candidates. Return JSON."</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Anchor reward to 20-50% of CAC, not to a round-number gut feel; let the agent recompute as CAC drifts.</item>
        <item>Always double-sided unless margin forbids; one-sided programs feel exploitative and the referee converts worse.</item>
        <item>Promote immediately after a "win moment" event (purchase complete, milestone reached, 5-star review submitted) — not on first visit.</item>
        <item>Build the dashboard before launch so the agent has clean event names to optimize against.</item>
        <item>Sunset or rotate the program every 6-9 months; static programs decay as your best advocates exhaust their networks.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs eagerly suggest "give 50% off" — always pass a hard max_reward_pct_of_cac constraint into the prompt.</item>
        <item>Fraud detection requires deterministic rules, not LLM judgment; agent should compute features (IP overlap, payment-method overlap, signup velocity) and pass to a rules engine, never decide bans alone.</item>
        <item>Reward fulfillment must be idempotent: if the agent retries the API call, do NOT double-credit. Use a unique (referrer_id, referee_id, event) key.</item>
        <item>Don't let the agent A/B-test reward amounts without finance approval — easy to blow burn budget.</item>
        <item>Translate legal copy through a human; incentivized referrals trigger different disclosure regimes per jurisdiction.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Fraud explosion: self-referrals, referral farms, multi-account abuse without deterministic detection rules.</description>
      <reason>Agents detect patterns but final ban decisions need human-in-loop. Deterministic feature computation (IP overlap, payment-method overlap, signup velocity) paired with rules-engine flags allows human review without LLM hallucination.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Mis-attribution when users clear cookies, switch devices, or use ad blockers — first-touch vs last-touch logic not explicit.</description>
      <reason>Attribution ambiguity must be resolved in writing before launch. Default to last-touch for simplicity unless you have cross-device tracking infrastructure; document the choice in every dashboard.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Reward fulfillment lag (manual credit approval) breaks the trust loop.</description>
      <reason>Requires idempotent automation. Use a unique (referrer_id, referee_id, event) key to make credit operations idempotent and reduce manual review to fraud exceptions only.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Viral coefficient (K) plateaus quickly; agents over-optimizing reward size erode margin without meaningful K lift.</description>
      <reason>K improves with friction reduction (invites/user = i) and conversion rate (c). Reward size affects only motivation; above-optimal rewards are pure expense. Focus agent optimization on cycle-time reduction and friction cuts first.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/landing-page.md" purpose="Referral program landing page copy with stats block and FAQ."/>
      <template path="templates/emails.md" purpose="Announcement and reminder email copy."/>
      <template path="templates/k_factor.py" purpose="Python helper to compute K from API/event data."/>
    </templates>

